title: Moths of Riddells Creek
description: Initial list and photos from Peter Marriott. Lots of other ID help from Peter, Marilyn Hewish and Wendy Moore.

items.title: Chrysolarentia vicissata
items.content_text: Not absolutely sure of the id.

items.title: Crypsiphona ocultaria
items.content_text: I found it on our French door fly wire.

items.title: Elhamma australasiae
items.content_text: Mum found this moth on my Dad's shirt! It hung from my arm. and it went on my hair and on my collar!

items.title: Endoxyla secta
items.content_text: On the ground so probably old/worn. ID by Marilyn Hewish.

items.title: Eucymatoge scotodes
items.content_text: Grey/dark form. This individual was very dark, almost black-looking. ID by Marilyn Hewish.

items.title: Phrissogonus laticostata
items.content_text: Small moth.

items.title: Epidesmia hypenaria
items.content_text: Could be the same or a different individual in the two pics.

items.title: Scioglyptis chionomera
items.content_text: Landed on my finger and was reluctant to leave.

items.title: Heliomystis electrica
items.content_text: Underwing orange-yellow.

items.title: Anthela acuta group
items.content_text: Could be the same or different individuals in the two pics.

items.title: Aenetus eximia
items.content_text: This record extends its known distribution, being the westernmost record of the species in Victoria. Third pic shows yellow wing underside of the female. The two wing spots are also a feature of the female.

items.title: Epidesmia hypenaria
items.content_text: Small moth in Conglomerate Gully, Riddells Creek.

items.title: Pollanisus viridipulverulenta, Turneriprocris dolens
items.content_text: T. dolens left. Found by Ellena Best at Conglomerate Gully.

items.title: Oenogenes fugalis
items.content_text: Moth on Chrysocepalum apiculatum (Common Everlasting)

items.title: Opodiphthera helena
items.content_text: Nice socks.

items.title: Hepialidae spp.
items.content_text: On wet, warmish autumn nights we get hundreds of rain moths - 17 on this window pane. Mostly O. dirempta/lyelli but occasional O. antipoda (or australis) and T. atripalpis. Tawny Frogmouths feast on them.

items.title: Epicoma sp. (1)
items.content_text: Always appears at this time of year.

items.title: Chelepteryx chalepteryx
items.content_text: Large moth out in the daytime - a few minutes after taking this photo it was taken by a Pied Currawong.

items.title: Monoctenia falernaria
items.content_text: Large moth.

items.title: Chrysolarentia lucidulata
items.content_text: Female. With wings closed for the few minutes I saw it. ID confirmed by PM.

items.title: Isotoma fluviatilis subsp. australis, Pollanisus viridipulver...
Glyphipterix chrysoplanetis, Isotoma fluviatilis subsp. austr...
3 ids
items.content_text: Forrester takes advantage of the slit in the Lobelia flower as the Glyphs look on (they tend to climb down to get their feed).

items.title: Phalaenoides glycinae
items.content_text: Feeding in planted Westringia.

items.title: Nyctemera amicus
items.content_text: Never seen one at night before - commonly seen as a day-flying moth.

items.title: Epicoma sp. (1)
items.content_text: 3rd pic collage shows upperside open and underside while flying against window. Different individuals photographed.

items.title: Spilosoma glatignyi
items.content_text: Different individuals photographed. 3-4 individuals flying around at the same time.

items.title: Abantiades labyrinthicus
items.content_text: Never convinced of IDing this species. Could be another Abantiades spp.. Very large moth - perhaps the largest species we get.

items.title: Endoxyla encalypti
items.content_text: Very large moth flew into window last night then remained there throughout today.

items.title: 29 ids
items.content_text: Survey at Treetops Scout Camp.

items.title: Hestiochora tricolor
items.content_text: Feeding in Blackberry.

items.title: Glyphipterix chrysoplanetis
items.content_text: Tiny sedge moth in large numbers on Senecio linearifolius var. linearifolius.

items.title: Chrysolarentia correlata
items.content_text: Distinctly yellow in flight and on landing. Gives a few wing flaps on landing before resting. This species might merge with C. insulsata (see CD that comes with Moths of Victoria 3). New species record for Riddells Creek.

items.title: Aenetus ligniveren
items.content_text: Found dead on the garden path this morning. Apparently males are rarely seen. New species record for Riddells Creek.

items.title: Taxeotis intextata
items.content_text: Looks like T. mimela but I'm told more likely to be T. intextata which was seen flying on this night. At a sheet setup during a joint RCLandcare-Entomological Society night.

items.title: Praxis edwardsii
items.content_text: New species record for Riddells Creek - at a sheet setup during a joint RCLandcare-Entomological Society night.

items.title: Unplaced severata
items.content_text: At a sheet setup during a joint RCLandcare-Entomological Society night. ID by MH.

items.title: Phelotis cognata
items.content_text: Near a sheet setup during a joint RCLandcare-Entomological Society night.

items.title: Chlorocoma sp. (3)
items.content_text: New species record for Riddells Creek - near a sheet setup during a joint RCLandcare-Entomological Society night. Identified using the Emerald moth key in the newly published 'Moths of Victoria 4'.

items.title: Epidesmia hypenaria
items.content_text: Wings held so moth looks triangular. Very long nose.

items.title: Pollanisus viridipulverulenta
items.content_text: About double the size of the similar-looking Turneriprocris dolens, which was flying on the same day - see previous observation, 7802.

items.title: Leucochrysum albicans var. albicans, Turneriprocris dolens
items.content_text: Moth is about half the size of the similar-looking Satin-green Forester, which was also about in large numbers this day (see following observation, 7803). T. dolens seen primarily on the Leucochrysum.

items.title: Pinara obliqua
items.content_text: female moth copper and brown dots on wings distinct brown diagonal line on wings strips on legs

items.title: Epicoma sp. (1)
items.content_text: Considerable colour variation. See 6163 and 6162 from the same night.

items.title: Epicoma sp. (1)
items.content_text: Considerable colour variation. See 6164 and 6162 from the same night.

items.content_text: Considerable colour variation. See 6163 and 6164 from the same night.

items.title: Oxycanus sirpus
items.content_text: ID by AK.

items.title: Chelepteryx chalepteryx
items.content_text: Flying against window.

items.title: Psilosticha absorpta
items.content_text: Possibly Phelotis cognata but doesn't quite fit?

items.title: Monopis icterogastra
items.content_text: Spotted by Lydia Best.

items.title: Xanthorhoe vacuaria
items.content_text: This moth lands and then pushes wings up and down a few times before resting. First pic is wings down, 2nd pic is wings up.

items.title: Maxates centrophylla
items.content_text: Apparently rarely seen, and mostly in the Dandenongs area near Melbourne so an unusual record.

items.title: Melanodes anthracitaria
items.content_text: Lydia spotted and IDed the moth, photo by Russell Best. New species for Riddells Creek. First pic is with flash on, second pic is same moth without flash. It looks black to the eye (not grey).

items.title: Genduara punctigera
items.content_text: On the trampoline net in garden - spotted by my daughter, Ellena.

items.title: Phalaenoides glycinae
items.content_text:
Moth wings open Black & White
side view body bright orange

items.title: Lepidoptera spp., Ninox novaeseelandiae
items.content_text: Southern Boobook feeding on moths at our lounge window after rain, which brought the moths.

items.title: Abantiades labyrinthicus
items.content_text: Could be Trictena atripalpis?

items.title: Hellula hydralis
items.content_text: Not sure of ID.

items.title: Lepidoptera spp.
items.content_text: Oecophorid?

items.title: Scioglyptis canescaria
items.content_text: Phelotis spp.?

items.title: Abantiades labyrinthicus, Lepidoptera spp.
items.content_text: Could be Trictena atripalpis? I struggle with these two species - even the CSIRO specimens on the web look the same for the two species.

items.title: Idaea halmaea
items.content_text: Geometrid, looks a bit like Scopula perlata.

items.title: Lepidoptera spp.
items.content_text: Pyralidae.

items.title: Chlorocoma carenaria
items.content_text: Small moth is Tortricidae spp. maybe?

items.title: Chelepteryx chalepteryx
items.content_text: No date available.

items.title: Epicoma sp. (1)
items.content_text: Moth appeared to play dead and flew off later.

items.title: Abantiades labyrinthicus
items.content_text: Very large moth, banged into the window. Not sure of ID.

items.title: Chrysocephalum apiculatum s.s., Pollanisus viridipulverulenta
items.content_text: Feeding on Chrysocephalum apiculatum.

items.title: Mnesampela privata
items.content_text: Mt Martha.

items.title: Capusa spp.
items.content_text: It isn't C.stenophara. Possibly C.senilis.
